Troubleshooting Tips
Issue: Application won't start

Check if port 8080 is already in use: netstat -tulpn | grep 8080
Kill existing process: pkill -f app.py
Restart application: python3 /opt/vulnerable-2fa-app/app.py &
Issue: Session tokens not captured

Verify requests library is installed: pip3 install requests
Check if cookies are enabled in session object
Print response headers to debug: print(response.headers)
Issue: Replay attack not working

Ensure you're using the correct token from the right stage
Check if tokens have expired (test immediately after capture)
Verify cookie names match exactly (case-sensitive)
Issue: Scripts produce errors

Check Python version: python3 --version (should be 3.6+)
Install missing dependencies: pip3 install -r requirements.txt
Review error messages for specific missing modules
Conclusion
This lab demonstrated critical vulnerabilities in two-factor authentication implementations. You learned to identify logic flaws, exploit session management weaknesses, and automate security testing. Key takeaways include:

Logic flaws are often more dangerous than technical vulnerabilities
Session management must be properly implemented at every authentication stage
Automation is essential for comprehensive security testing
Defense in depth requires multiple layers of validation
Remediation Best Practices:

Regenerate session IDs after each authentication stage
Implement strict server-side validation for all authentication steps
Enforce rate limiting on 2FA attempts
Set appropriate token expiration times
Invalidate old sessions when new ones are created
Never trust client-side validation alone
Ethical Considerations: Always obtain proper authorization before testing 2FA implementations. Use these techniques only in controlled environments or with explicit permission. Document all findings professionally and provide actionable remediation guidance.

Continue practicing these techniques in authorized environments to strengthen your security assessment skills.
